.TH "SANITIZER.GET" "3JS" "January 16, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Sanitizer.get \- Sanitizer: get() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]get()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R]
interface returns a \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] dictionary instance that
represents the current \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] configuration.
.PP
This may be used to create a sanitizer that is slightly modified from
the default; by first getting and then modifying the default sanitizer
configuration, and then using it to construct a new sanitizer.
.PP
The returned configuration can also be used to inspect the
configuration, and can be passed directly the HTML parsing functions.
Note however that it will be more efficient to pass a
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] rather than a configuration dictionary,
particularly where the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] is to be used multiple
times.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
get()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None
.SS Return value
A \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Getting a configuration
This example shows how you might create a new sanitizer and get its
configuration.
.SS JavaScript
The following code tests whether the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface is
supported, and if so creates a new \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object using a
simple \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] that allows the HTML elements:
\f[CR]<div>\f[R], \f[CR]<p>\f[R], \f[CR]<span>\f[R],
\f[CR]<script>\f[R].
It then gets and logs the configuration.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create sanitizer using SanitizerConfig\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({ elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqp\(dq, \(dqspan\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq] });

\f[I]// Get current configuration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizerConfig = sanitizer.get();

log(JSON.stringify(sanitizerConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.SS Results
The output is logged below.
Note that the same elements set when constructing the sanitizer are
returned, but the new elements also have a namespace.
Note also here that comments and data attributes will be allowed.
.SS Getting the default sanitizer
This example shows how you can get the configuration for the default
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R].
This might then be modified and used to create a new
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] that meets your specific needs.
.SS JavaScript
The following code tests whether the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface is
supported.
It then creates the default \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R], passing no options,
and then gets and logs the configuration.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create default sanitizer\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer();

\f[I]// Get default configuration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] defaultConfig = sanitizer.get();

log(JSON.stringify(defaultConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.SS Results
The default sanitizer configuration is logged below.
Note that the default configuration is quite big, allowing many elements
and attributes.
